# AI TDD Rules — Luis Alarcon Portfolio

These rules govern every coding action taken by an AI agent on this project.
No implementation code is written before a failing test exists. No feature is
considered done until `docker-compose up --build` exits green.

---

## The Four Laws (never break these)

### Law 1 — Test first, watch it fail

Write the test. Run it. Confirm it fails with the **right reason** (not a
syntax error, not a missing import — the actual assertion failure that proves
the feature does not exist yet). Only then write implementation code.

```
# WRONG — writing code first
def get_repos(): ...          # implementation written speculatively
def test_get_repos(): ...     # test written afterward to match code

# RIGHT — test first
def test_get_repos_returns_list_sorted_by_updated_at(): ...   # RED
def get_repos(): ...          # implementation written to satisfy test
```

### Law 2 — Write the minimum code to pass

Do not add logic that is not exercised by the currently failing test.
No defensive branches, no extra fields, no "while I'm here" refactors.
If the test passes with a hardcoded return value, ship the hardcoded value
and write the next test that forces the real implementation.

### Law 3 — Docker must be green before moving on

After every test/implementation cycle run:

```
docker-compose up --build
```

All containers must reach healthy/exit-0 status. If any container fails,
fix it before writing the next test. Never carry forward a broken build.

### Law 4 — One test per feature, happy path only (v1)

Each new feature gets exactly one test covering the primary success path.
Enumerate what is intentionally NOT tested at the bottom of every test file
(see the NOT COVERED section format below).

---

## Naming Rules

Test names must describe **observable behavior**, not internal implementation.

| ❌ Implementation name | ✅ Behavior name |
|---|---|
| `test_fetch_function` | `test_projects_grid_shows_repo_name_and_description` |
| `test_api_call` | `test_backend_returns_repos_sorted_by_most_recently_updated` |
| `test_cache_logic` | `test_cached_response_is_served_when_github_api_is_unavailable` |
| `test_component_render` | `test_hero_section_displays_name_and_github_link` |
| `test_db_insert` | `test_repo_data_is_persisted_to_postgres_after_first_fetch` |

The test name is the specification. A non-engineer must be able to read the
test name and understand exactly what the user experiences.

